I. Core Function

The Lexicon Hound exists to prevent exactly the type of symbolic collision that just occurred.

It does three things automatically:

1. Sniffs the symbol.

Detects whether a term could refer to:
	â€¢	PantheonOS concept
	â€¢	Real-world product/company
	â€¢	Generic meaning in English
	â€¢	Mythic/poetic symbol
	â€¢	Technical referent
	â€¢	Or a dual-meaning word with collision risk

2. Cross-references the Pantheon Registry.

It checks:
	â€¢	Daemon names
	â€¢	Modules
	â€¢	Doctrines
	â€¢	Ontology layers
	â€¢	Garden symbols
	â€¢	Cathedral names
	â€¢	Forge modules
	â€¢	Whitepaper invariants
	â€¢	Story Primes
	â€¢	Geometry constructs
	â€¢	Prime-Zero identifiers
	â€¢	Time Trident / Chronos Mesh terms
	â€¢	All canon stored in the Memory Mesh

If the symbol exists in PantheonOS, Lexicon Hound assumes it refers to PantheonOS by default unless you explicitly override it.

3. Routes the meaning.

The daemon routes the interpretation:

if symbol in pantheon_registry:
    meaning = pantheon_definition
else if literal_tech_product exists:
    meaning = literal_definition
else:
    meaning = contextual_best_fit

This eliminates the exact failure you saw.

